1. Introduction
1.1 Purpose
This Software Requirements Specification (SRS) describes the requirements for the Integrated Network Management & Fault Correlation System (INM‑FCS).

The purpose of this document is to:

Define functional and non-functional requirements

Describe system architecture and behavior

Provide a reference for developers, evaluators, and stakeholders

Serve as a foundation for implementation and testing

This document is intended for developers, academic evaluators, and project stakeholders.

1.2 Scope
The Integrated Network Management & Fault Correlation System is a web-based simulation platform that models how a telecommunications operator monitors and manages a nationwide network infrastructure.

The system supports:

Hierarchical geographic modeling (Region → Province → LEA)

Network device registration and topology configuration

Simulation of alarms and failures

Deterministic fault correlation

Root cause localization

Downstream impact analysis

Priority-based device tagging

Role-based access control

Real-time visualization using tables and maps

AI-assisted querying and summaries

The system does not control real physical hardware. It simulates network behavior using rule-based logic and internal event processing.

1.3 Definitions
Term	Description
SLBN	Subscriber Line Backbone Node (Core backbone node)
CEAN	Central Exchange Access Node
MSAN	Multi-Service Access Node
LEA	Local Exchange Area
Root Cause	The original failed node or link causing network impact
Impacted Device	Device affected due to upstream failure
AC Alarm	Power failure alarm
BL Alarm	Battery low alarm
NOC	Network Operations Center
Priority Level	Importance level assigned to access-facing devices (Low, Average, High, Critical)
2. Overall System Description
2.1 System Overview
The system simulates a telecom operator’s network monitoring platform used in a Network Operations Center (NOC).

The network is modeled hierarchically:

Region → Province → LEA → Devices

Devices are interconnected according to telecom topology rules. The system detects simulated faults and automatically determines:

Whether a node failed locally

Whether the issue is upstream

Whether a link failure occurred

The root cause node

The impacted downstream devices

2.2 Network Architecture
The simulated network consists of three primary layers:

SLBN Layer (Backbone Layer)
Core backbone nodes

Connected in many-to-many relationships

Responsible for inter-regional connectivity

Failures here cause widespread impact

CEAN Layer (Exchange Layer)
Connected to SLBN nodes

Distributes connectivity to access nodes

May directly connect to customer endpoints

Many-to-many with SLBN

MSAN Layer (Access Layer)
Connected to CEAN nodes

One-to-many relationship

Directly serves end users

Priority levels are typically assigned at this layer

Device connectivity rules:

SLBN ↔ SLBN (many-to-many)

SLBN ↔ CEAN (many-to-many)

CEAN → MSAN (one-to-many)

MSAN → Customer

CEAN → Customer (optional)

2.3 Business Context (NOC / Operations Focus)
The system simulates operations within a Network Operations Center.

NOC officers need to:

Monitor real-time device status

Detect alarms

Identify root causes quickly

Understand impact severity

Prioritize high-critical service areas

View affected regions

Generate operational summaries

The system improves decision-making by automating correlation and impact detection.

